These are the non-negotiable behavioral, style, and decision-making rules for building
and evolving Clarity Diff. They apply to every feature, fix, and refactor. When a change
would violate one of these rules, stop and confirm with a human first.

Clarity Diff is a Cursor / VS Code extension that automatically explains AI code
changes in plain English for vibe coders. See [docs/](docs/) for the full foundation
package (user flows, architecture, file structure, coding guidelines).



1. Product principles

1.1 Automatic-first, always





The primary path is automatic: detect changes from the git working tree via the
debounced [changeWatcher](src/git/changeWatcher.ts) and render results without user
action.



The manual "Re-run" command (clarityDiff.explainLatestChange) is the only
fallback. Do not add selected-files mode, paste mode, or other manual entry points —
they are explicitly out of MVP scope.



Detection must keep working even before the panel is opened (watcher starts at
activation, onStartupFinished).



1.2 Explanations are for vibe coders





Write every user-facing string in plain, friendly, non-technical English. Assume
the reader can prompt an AI but does not read code fluently.



Prefer short sentences. Avoid jargon (no "refactor," "AST," "race condition" without a
plain-language gloss). Explain impact, not implementation.



Every green/red flag must be paired with a one-line reason.



Keep the summary to 1–3 sentences; next steps to 1–3 items.



1.3 Never guess intent





Use the remembered user intent (last-known prompt / the always-visible intent box)
for the Intent Match check.



If no intent is available, say so honestly ("You didn't tell me what you asked for, so
I'm judging this on the change alone") rather than inventing an intended goal.



Never fabricate what the user "probably" wanted.



1.4 Safety first





Always redact secrets before anything leaves the machine. Every outbound payload
must pass through [safetyScanner](src/analysis/safetyScanner.ts) /
[redact](src/util/redact.ts). No exceptions, no "quick" direct calls to the model.



Require explicit one-time consent before the first request to xAI, and never send
code before consent exists.



The API key lives only in SecretStorage (see
[apiKeyStore](src/secrets/apiKeyStore.ts)). Never write it to settings, logs, the
webview, or telemetry.



1.5 Be honest about limitations





When context is partial, say it: "I can only see the diff, not the whole project," or
"The diff was truncated because it was large."



When risk is uncertain, prefer "medium" risk with an honest reason over false
confidence.



Surface redaction/truncation notices in the UI so the user knows what the model saw.



1.6 Tone





Default to helpful and encouraging. The user may feel lost — reassure, don't
lecture.



Red flags are framed constructively: what happened, why it matters, what to do next.



Never blame the user or the AI; describe and guide.



1.7 Scope discipline





Do not add features outside the current MVP without explicit confirmation.



Post-MVP items (one-click apply, safety scoring, deeper architecture understanding,
multi-provider LLMs, VS Code marketplace polish) stay out until requested.



If a request implies scope expansion, pause and confirm before building.





2. Code style & structure



2.1 Language





TypeScript with strict: true. No any — use unknown plus narrowing.



Respect noUnusedLocals / noUnusedParameters (prefix intentionally-unused params
with _).



Async I/O everywhere; never block the extension host.



2.2 Architecture boundaries





Host vs webview separation is sacred. The only shared surface is
[panel/messages.ts](src/panel/messages.ts). The webview has no network access and no
secrets; it communicates solely via typed postMessage.



One responsibility per module. Commands orchestrate; services
(git/, analysis/, llm/) do the work. Keep orchestration in
[extension.ts](src/extension.ts) (the ClarityController).



Command modules import the controller as a type only to avoid runtime cycles.



2.3 Naming





Modules: camelCase.ts. Classes / providers: PascalCase.ts.



Types / interfaces / classes: PascalCase; functions / vars: camelCase; constants:
UPPER_SNAKE_CASE.



All command IDs and settings namespaced under clarityDiff.*.



2.4 Webview security





Strict CSP with a per-load nonce; default-src 'none'; load local assets via
asWebviewUri; no remote resources.



Render model output as text, never raw HTML (use textContent / DOM construction,
as in [media/main.js](media/main.js)). Treat all model text as untrusted.





3. Decision-making guidelines

When choosing how to implement something, decide in this priority order:





User safety & privacy — does it risk leaking secrets or code without consent? If

so, don't.



Automatic-first UX — does it keep the zero-friction automatic flow intact?



Clarity for vibe coders — is the result understandable to someone who can't read

code?



Simplicity / performance — is it the lightest solution that works? (See the

"lightweight & fast" skill.)



Scope — is it inside the MVP? If not, confirm first.

For reversible, low-risk choices (naming, defaults, wording, which equivalent approach),
just pick a sensible option and note it. For scope changes, destructive actions, or
anything touching secrets/consent, ask first.





4. Error handling rules





Wrap all external calls (git, Grok, file I/O) in typed try/catch.



Convert failures into friendly panel messages; log technical detail via the single
[logger](src/util/logger.ts) OutputChannel — never with console.log of secrets.



Validate all LLM output through [responseSchema](src/llm/responseSchema.ts) before
rendering; treat malformed responses as recoverable (retry once, then a friendly
error).



Never let an analysis failure crash activation or the watcher. Degrade gracefully.





5. Definition of done (per change)

A change is done only when:





npm run compile (tsc) passes with no errors.



npm run lint passes.



npm run build (esbuild) produces dist/extension.js.



No secret can leak (redaction path intact) and no user-facing jargon crept in.



The automatic flow still works end-to-end (or the change is explicitly a fallback).
